The Five Cities form a co-dependent trade and legal network, not a military alliance. Each fills one role in a chain: Midgaard (origin claim and inland legitimacy), Kiess (overland custody and legal memory on Roc Road), Rakuen (southern route resilience and disaster absorption), Kowloon (northern throughput coordination), Mafdet (ocean transfer and maritime conversion). The chain functions as: origin claim → overland custody → dispute adjudication → hazard screening → ocean transfer. Remove any one city and the others accumulate strain in specific, predictable ways. This is a co-dependency none of the five fully chose and none can easily exit. Grand arc of five-city interaction: Post-Evermeet Recovery (Kiess and Midgaard stabilize replacement arbitration; Kowloon consolidates northern collection routes); Lantern-Delta Expansion (road-watch synchronization; Rakuen receives planned migration under frontier policy; Mafdet operates as independent harbor); Violet Compact (Midgaard's Sealed Names apparatus routes displaced populations to Rakuen; Kiess contests sealed-order governance; Mafdet formalizes the Strandline Compact); Ashfall Decades (Cinderteeth disruptions force emergency rerouting; multi-year Rakuen rationing; Mafdet's role expands for off-continent diversion; Kowloon's emergency grain protocols begin servicing Rakuen); Three annexation petitions and three refusals; Modern era (all five cooperate on fraud suppression and anti-counterfeit protocols while competing over seal authority, narrative primacy, and whose classification is final in disputed cases). Current flashpoints: the annexation question (Rakuen's Amendment Track may submit a fourth petition with Kiess certification), seal sovereignty wars (whose institutional seal is dispositive in fraud investigations), the Conclave guilt chain (three cities documented in the condemned-debtor transfer apparatus), and casualty accountability (whose records govern unidentified dead along contested corridors).

