Midgaard's position in the five-city network is the inland legitimacy engine that all others must reckon with regardless of whether they want to: charter arbitration authority, sealed-warrant governance, and the registry prestige that validates overland provenance. The network's most politically layered bilateral relationship is Midgaard-Rakuen: three refused annexation petitions, the Accounting War (both cities maintain internally consistent but mutually incompatible classifications of the same aid events), the Resettlement Record (Rakuen's Garden Ledger holds the most complete evidence of the Violet Compact's testimony-suppression mechanism), and the circular dependency that keeps the Reckoning faction's access to the Garden Ledger blocked by the same Continuity faction that controls access to Midgaard's sealed cross-reference archives. The network's deepest shared guilt connects Midgaard and Kowloon through parallel condemned-debtor transfer records (Granite Arcade ledger and Black Ledger), and adds Rakuen as the third point — the geography where transferred persons' testimonies were subsequently suppressed through Kel'Shadra. Midgaard's Reckoning faction has an institutional interest in Rakuen remaining independent because independent Rakuen controls an independent archive; absorption would bring Garden Ledger records under Continuity faction access controls. The seal sovereignty war is Midgaard's to lose: archive precedence (Midgaard's claim) versus dock attestation finality (Mafdet's claim) versus due-process sequence (Kiess's claim) — no supreme tribunal exists to resolve impasse.

