Rakuen carries costs the other four classify away: founded to escape Midgaard's registry culture, now unable to survive without Midgaard's subsidy pipeline; founded on shared surplus and low-wall principle, now operating ration towers and labor drafts; petitioned three times for annexation, refused three times, now navigating three mutually incompatible factional responses. The Amendment Track (fourth petition with Kiess certification), Quiet Separatists (maritime route through Mafdet bypassing Midgaard), and Preservation Coalition (status quo dependency) disagree not only on tactics but on what Rakuen is supposed to be. The Garden Ledger Clerks represent the institutional continuity of the founding accounting vision — open records, publicly readable — now operating in tension with a Bloom Council that approved the sanitized Paradise Thesis and negotiated the Resettlement Charter. The Kel'Shadra witnessing office closure left records in the crypt apparatus that concern Rakuen arrivals who had inconvenient things to say about who ordered their resettlement and why. Rakuen is the third point on the triangular Conclave evidence structure: not a transfer participant but the geography that made transferred persons' testimonies invisible. Its independent Garden Ledger is the archive that the Reckoning faction across three cities needs to see; its annexation into Midgaard would bring those records under Continuity faction access controls; the annexation refusals, whatever their stated reasons, produce the outcome of keeping the third evidence point out of Midgaard's institutional reach.

