The five-city network's most significant absent elements: Midgaard's Unindexed Years (ledger gaps coinciding with peak Conclave transfer activity), Kowloon's Black Ledger (unconfirmed sealed cistern, original unredacted founding census), Rakuen's Garden Ledger access (blocked by circular cross-reference dependency that Continuity factions maintain by controlling both sealed archives simultaneously), Kiess's "Received Southern Documents, Violet Era" collection (neither confirmed nor denied to contain the unedited Paradise Thesis), and the Kel'Shadra witnessing office records (somewhere in crypt apparatus, inaccessible through standard descent pathways). The three-point triangular evidence structure — Midgaard's trade ledger, Kowloon's Black Ledger, Rakuen's Garden Ledger — is the most complete potential documentary case for institutional accountability in the network's history. All three are currently inaccessible through different mechanisms: Midgaard's by Continuity faction access control, Kowloon's by physical concealment (if it exists), Rakuen's by the cross-reference dependency that Continuity faction control of Midgaard's sealed archives maintains. The five-city network's seal sovereignty disputes are also disputes about whose institutional seal determines which absences are legally significant and whose silences are dispositive. There is no supreme tribunal. Seal disputes that reach impasse become standing grievances that recur in modified form.

