The five-city annexation arc is the clearest modern case of responsibility without incorporation in Kiess legal scholarship. Three doctrines now taught from this case: emergency testimony resilience (when records are repeatedly destroyed, admissibility standards must preserve witness dignity without collapsing evidentiary thresholds), externalization review (upstream powers cannot treat downstream casualties as statistical variance indefinitely without legitimacy erosion), and contradiction preservation (institutional archives should retain unresolved disagreement rather than enforce single-line narrative closure). From Ushabti analytical perspective: the three annexation refusals constitute three evidentiary data points on a claim (Midgaard refuses annexation regardless of Rakuen's stated compliance with stated conditions). The claim is that the stated conditions were not the operative conditions. The evidence is: Southmark Petition refused for stated reason X; Rakuen addressed X; Ash Plea refused for different stated reason Y; Y was not addressed by either party; Iron Compact Appeal refused for yet different stated reason Z; Z was not addressed. Pattern: three different stated reasons, each cited as the barrier, none proven operative by being removed to test whether removal produced annexation. The Garden Ledger Clerks' analysis of this pattern — stated barriers were pretextual and the consistent underlying answer was absorption creates obligations — is an evidentiary argument, not a political accusation. It requires rebuttal through evidence, not through authority claims.

