The five-city network's functional interdependencies are measurable through cascade analysis: remove Midgaard (lose inland registry legitimacy and road-warden funding; Kiess loses its intelligence pipeline and provisioning doctrine partner; Rakuen loses its primary subsidy pipeline); remove Kowloon (lose northern throughput, Southern Grain Compact activation capacity, and the primary northern maritime conversion link to Mafdet); remove Kiess (lose the western frontier intelligence, anti-sealed-warrant legal constraint on Midgaard's governance tendencies, and the legal certification mechanism that could validate a Rakuen fourth petition); remove Rakuen (lose southern route resilience broker and the most complete archive of evidence connecting the Conclave transfer chain's three evidence points); remove Mafdet (lose maritime export conversion, Quarantine Ledger hazard containment, and the mercy-freight mechanism that serves as Rakuen's emergency release valve when overland routes fail). Each removal has downstream cascade effects on the remaining four. The network's co-dependency is not symmetric: Midgaard can absorb the loss of any one other city more easily than any other city can absorb the loss of Midgaard; Mafdet can survive independently through maritime routes; Kowloon's institutional stability would outlast most shocks; Kiess is most vulnerable to Midgaard disruption through its Roc Road commercial lifeline; Rakuen is most vulnerable to any combination of two or more partner failures occurring simultaneously.

