The five-city network's Accounting War (Midgaard classifies same events as "route-variance events"; Rakuen classifies same events as "subsidy contract non-performance") has a specific empirical resolution mechanism that neither side has invoked: a neutral third-party audit using both cities' baseline figures and the same events to determine which classification framework produces predictions that match observed outcomes. The question is not which classification is philosophically correct but which classification accurately predicted what obligations were generated, what was delivered, and what the deficit was. Rakuen's Garden Ledger casualty records attached to the Ash Plea constitute the empirical baseline for one measurement: documented deaths during a period when Midgaard classified its aid as sufficient under its framework. The Southern Grain Compact (Kowloon-Rakuen) provides a comparison case: a binding framework with defined trigger conditions and measured delivery times (two weeks from formal declaration). The Compact has been activated four times in sixty years with documented outcomes. The Kowloon-Rakuen framework demonstrates that binding commitments with defined triggers and measured delivery protocols produce different outcomes than "variance relief" with no binding obligation. The measurement question is: what would documented casualty counts have been under a binding-commitment framework versus the non-binding framework that actually applied? This question has not been formally asked by any neutral party in five-city proceedings.
